@@yThe Wizard's Keep@@N

@@eThe Wizard's Keep is not a wizard's vanity tower. It is a post-catastrophe
containment school built to solve a political problem: how to train
arcanists useful to civic powers without repeating the mountain-scale abuses
of the Spirebound Conclave.@@N

@@dIts founding charter was written in the shadow of Conclave revelations
about prisoner experimentation. The guiding doctrine was simple: arcane
competence should be reproducible by institution, not dependent on singular,
secretive masters. No unsupervised field trials. No off-ledger apprentices.
No research wing beyond posted watch distance. Every adept tied to a legal
witness chain.@@N

@@yThe Keep survives by balancing three incompatible mandates: instruction to
produce competent practitioners, custody to control dangerous knowledge, and
deniability to hide methods that would trigger intercity panic.@@N

@@eThat balance is visibly failing. Bricked-over doors, burned archives,
unfinished passages, and personnel whose loyalty is magical rather than civic
mark the institution's fracture lines. Early collegium culture gave way to
compartmentalization after information leaks: runed doors requiring keyword
authorization, lobby loops to separate traffic classes, and sealed side doors
where obsolete wings were quietly erased.@@N

@@dThe Burnt Records Incident left focused fire damage on concealed shelving
and paper stores, with at least one sealed iron lockbox preserved. This was
not panic destruction but institutionally sanctioned deletion.@@N

@@rBehind the formal northern lock lies an obsidian corridor terminating at a
blank wall with a circular groove: evidence of a removed or disabled
mechanism. A former deep-access interface, intentionally decommissioned
without full demolition. In contemporary rumor it is called 'the road that
used to continue.' Officially it does not exist.@@N

@@eThe Keep is what happens when a civilization decides magic must be governed
but cannot agree on who deserves to know the cost of governance.@@N
